dspace-development.title: Symplectic Elements: Missing Results for Specific Query

comments.body: The support specialist from Symplectic has requested the logs from the server in order to diagnose the issue. I shall proceed by providing these.

Attempting to retrieve the logs from Symplectic yields the following:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/dddc4eaa-cfff-4c1a-bc61-e1e91ecca4c2)

After refining the search to a more restricted date range, I was able to successfully provide the logs to Elements. Additionally, the support specialist also provided guidance as to where I may find server-side logs, and I provided some small set of these. Their response was the following:

```bash
Thanks for these. Looking at the System Log, the first thing I want to check on is whether you know why the website application is being started and shut down every day -- or, at least, every day in the logs you sent. 
​
I'm beginning to wonder if the re-indexer won't complete because it's already running when you ask it to re-index. I recall seeing something like that a few years ago, but you've got a pretty old version of Elements. The solution might be going into the directory and manually deleting the Search.Index, then letting it rebuild from scratch, but I hesitate to recommend something that drastic without consulting with a Dev. Unfortunately, it's too late in the day for me to get help from anyone in London, so I'm afraid we'll need to wait for Monday.
```

Hence I will delay resuming this until Monday.

comments.body: @carolyncole is concerned about the maintenance burden in playbooks, and specifically about the possibility of drift between staging and production playbooks. This led to a conversation about the way the repo currently handles groups in the hosts file, group_vars, role variables, and playbooks. Can we have a single playbook per project, with both the target hosts and the variables determined at runtime (for example, something like `ansible-playbook playbooks/pulmap.yml -e env=prod` and `ansible-playbook playbooks/pulmap.yml -e env=staging` instead of separate playbooks `pulmap_production.yml` and `pulmap_staging.yml`? This would reduce both maintenance and drift.
providing the stage at playbook runtime seems fine to me.
